[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Including the `id` of an element as an attribute selector rather than an id selector is a good way to make an element more specific without adding an overabundance of specificity.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] In the previous example, the selector `[id="myContent"]` counts as an attribute selector for the purpose of determining the selector's specificity, even though it selects an ID.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] You can also include the `id` or any part of a selector as a parameter in the `:where()` specificity-adjustment pseudo class if you need to make a selector more specific but don't want to add any specificity at all.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] As a special case for increasing specificity, you can duplicate weights from the *CLASS* or *ID* columns.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Duplicating id, class, pseudo-class or attribute selectors within a compound selector will increase specificity when overriding very specific selectors over which you have no control.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] If using selector duplication, always comment your CSS.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Leveraging cascade layers is the standard way of enabling one set of styles to take precedence over another set of styles; cascade layers enable this without using specificity!
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Normal (not important) author styles imported into cascade layers have lower precedence than unlayered author styles.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] If styles are coming from a stylesheet you can't edit or don't understand and you need to override styles, a strategy is to import the styles you don't control into a cascade layer.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Styles in subsequently declared layers take precedence, with unlayered styles having precedence over all layered styles from the same origin.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] When two selectors from different layers match the same element, origin and importance take precedence; the specificity of the selector in the losing stylesheet is irrelevant.
