[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] The best approach is to not use `!important`.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] The above explanations on specificity should be helpful in avoiding using the flag and removing it altogether when encountered.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] All these methods are covered in preceding sections.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] If you're unable to remove `!important` flags from an authors style sheet, the only solution to overriding the important styles is by using `!important`.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Creating a cascade layer of important declaration overrides is an excellent solution.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Import this stylesheet as the first import in your CSS using `layer()`, including the `@import` statement, before linking to other stylesheets.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] This is to ensure that the important overrides is imported as the first layer.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Each time you need to override an important declaration, declare it within the named layer.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Only declare important rules within the layer.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] The specificity of the selector of the important style within the layer can be low, as long as it matches the element you are trying to override.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Normal layers should be declared outside the layer because layered styles have lower precedence than unlayered styles.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] The proximity of an element to other elements that are referenced in a given selector has no impact on specificity.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] The `<h1>` elements will be purple because when declarations have the same specificity, the last declared selector has precedence.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] Styles for a directly targeted element will always take precedence over inherited styles, regardless of the specificity of the inherited rule.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] The `h1` will be purple because the `h1` selector targets the element specifically, while the green is inherited from the `#parent` declarations.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] In the following CSS, we have three selectors targeting `<input>` elements to set a color.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] If the above selectors all target the same input, the input will be red, as the first declaration has the highest value in the *ID* column.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] The last selector has four *TYPE* components.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] While it has the highest integer value, no matter how many elements and pseudo-elements are included, even if there were 150, TYPE components never have precedence over *CLASS* components.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] The column values are compared starting from left to right when column values are equal.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] When multiple declarations have equal specificity, the last declaration found in the CSS is applied to the element.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] If both selectors match the same `<input>`, the color will be blue.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] When two selectors in the same cascade layer and origin have the same specificity, scoping proximity is then calculated; the ruleset with the lowest scoping proximity wins.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] If scope proximity is also the same for both selectors, source order then comes into play.
[src:css-cascade-layers/css-specificity] When all else is equal, the last selector wins.
