[src:css-cascade-layers/csslayerblockrule] The **`CSSLayerBlockRule`** represents a `@layer` block rule.
[src:css-cascade-layers/csslayerblockrule] A string containing the name of the associated cascade layer.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] The **`revert-layer`** CSS-wide keyword rolls back the value of a property in a cascade layer to the value of the property in a CSS rule matching the element in a previous cascade layer.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] The value of a property with this keyword is recalculated as if no rules were specified on the target element in the current cascade layer.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] If there is no other cascade layer to revert to for the matching CSS rule, the property value rolls back to the computed value derived from the current layer.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] Furthermore, if there is no matching CSS rule in the current layer, the property value for the element rolls back to the style defined in a previous style origin.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] This keyword can be applied to any CSS property, including the CSS shorthand property `all`.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] The `revert-layer` keyword lets you rollback styles to those specified in previous cascade layers within the author origin.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] The `revert` keyword, in comparison, lets you roll back styles applied in the author origin to those specified in the user origin or user-agent origin.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] The `revert-layer` keyword is ideally meant to be applied to properties within a cascade layer.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] However, if applied to properties outside a cascade layer, it rolls back property values to any values set by presentational hints (such as `width` and `height` attributes or the `<s>` element in HTML), defaulting to the values established by the user agent's stylesheet or user styles.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] Unlike the `revert` keyword, which considers presentational hints as part of the author origin and reverts them as well, the `revert-layer` keyword ignores presentational hints outside the cascade layer, so it does not revert them.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] In the example below, two cascade layers are defined in the CSS, `base` and `special`.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] By default, rules in the `special` layer will override competing rules in the `base` layer because `special` is listed after `base` in the `@layer` declaration statement.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] All the `<li>` elements match the `item` rule in the `special` layer and are red.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] This is the default cascade layer behavior, where rules in the `special` layer take precedence over rules in the `base` layer.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] Let's examine how the `revert-layer` keyword changes the default cascade layer behavior.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] For this example, the `special` layer contains an additional `feature` rule targeting the first `<li>` element.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] The `color` property in this rule is set to `revert-layer`.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] With `color` set to `revert-layer`, the `color` property value rolls back to the value in the matching `feature` rule in the previous layer `base`, and so 'Item one' is now green.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] This example shows the `revert-layer` keyword behavior when there is no cascade layer to revert to *and* there is no matching CSS rule in the current layer to inherit the property value.
[src:css-cascade-layers/revert-layer] The style for all `<li>` elements rolls back to the defaults in the user-agent origin.
